Choice Engine / Preference Arena v1.0

Core claim

A lot of identity is easier to reveal through constrained choice than through open-ended description.

Not:
“What do you like?”

But:
“Which do you like more?”

That is the primitive.

One-line framing

Choice Engine is a universal pairwise preference system that discovers favorites, rankings, taste geometry, and identity signals by repeatedly asking the user to choose between two candidates.

⸻

Core abstractions

1. Preference Arena

A bounded space where two entities enter and one is preferred.

This is the universal stage.

Examples:
	•	Pokémon vs Pokémon
	•	Movie vs movie
	•	Team vs team
	•	Logo vs logo
	•	Aesthetic vs aesthetic
	•	Idea vs idea

The arena is not about truth. It is about revealed preference under constraint.

2. Champion–Challenger loop

One item is the current champion. A challenger appears. The user decides whether the crown changes hands.

This creates:
	•	drama
	•	continuity
	•	memory
	•	narrative attachment

It also makes ranking emotionally legible.

3. On-Deck buffer

A maybe-zone for uncertain or close-call contenders.

This is not just UX sugar. It captures something deep:

uncertainty is signal

The on-deck layer tracks edge cases, unresolved identity zones, and aesthetic boundary objects.

4. Pairwise decision manifold

Every decision is a local movement across a latent taste landscape.

The user is not merely choosing an object. They are revealing:
	•	what dimensions matter
	•	what tradeoffs they tolerate
	•	what wins under pressure

5. Taste Vector

A compressed fingerprint of preference built from repeated choices.

Example dimensions:
	•	dark vs bright
	•	sleek vs goofy
	•	cute vs menacing
	•	nostalgic vs modern
	•	minimal vs ornate
	•	elegant vs chaotic

The app starts with choices.
It ends with a computational portrait.

6. Preference Lattice

A hierarchical network of liked things, near-likes, rejected things, and ambiguous things.

Not all preferences are flat rankings. Some are clustered, conditional, or domain-specific.

A lattice handles:
	•	favorites
	•	runner-ups
	•	category winners
	•	contradictions
	•	context shifts

7. Rank under uncertainty

A favorite is not always a fixed absolute. It is often a stable result inside a confidence band.

That means the engine can say:
	•	“Your favorite is probably Umbreon”
	•	“Your top three are close”
	•	“Your taste becomes unstable when nostalgia and coolness conflict”

That is much more honest and much more useful.

⸻

Why this matters

Most systems ask for explicit identity labels.

This one infers identity through repeated micro-decisions.

That is powerful because people are often bad at directly stating what they like, but much better at comparing two things in the moment.

So this becomes a more truthful mirror.

