Pantheon mappings

Mirror

Mirror is the obvious one.

Choice Engine acts like a reflective surface:
	•	it shows the user what they actually pick
	•	not what they claim to be
	•	not what they wish they liked
	•	what consistently wins

Mirror function:
self-revelation through preference

Spider

Spider maps relations:
	•	entity-to-entity similarity
	•	user-to-entity attraction
	•	cluster emergence
	•	latent taste neighborhoods

Spider function:
build the web of preference relations

Hound

Hound watches for anomalies:
	•	inconsistent choices
	•	abrupt reversals
	•	manipulated inputs
	•	mood-driven deviations
	•	strategic rather than authentic picking

Hound function:
detect noise, drift, and adversarial distortion

Mother Duck

Mother Duck holds the comparison ledger:
	•	all choices
	•	timestamps
	•	hesitation
	•	reversals
	•	category-specific patterns

Mother Duck function:
preserve the trail of becoming

Dragonfly

Dragonfly reframes “favorite” from a fixed answer into a dynamic identity event.

Dragonfly function:
transform ranking into meaning

Atlas Kernel

Atlas can use pairwise preference as a canonical input channel for self-modeling and recommendation.

Atlas function:
