Higher-order abstractions

A vs B as cognition primitive

This may be the deepest abstraction here.

A vs B is not just an app mechanic. It is a general reasoning primitive.

Humans often understand themselves and the world through contrast:
	•	this or that
	•	more or less
	•	better or worse
	•	me or not-me

So Choice Engine is a formalized version of a very old cognitive motion.

Constraint reveals structure

Open freedom produces vagueness. Constraint produces signal.

By narrowing the question to a pair, the system forces the user’s internal weighting function to show itself.

That is why this works so well.

Uncertainty is part of identity

Most systems try to erase maybe.

This one preserves it.

That matters because:
	•	ambiguity zones are real
	•	unresolved preferences carry signal
	•	identity often lives at the boundary, not only at the peak

Preference is relational, not isolated

No object is liked in a vacuum.

A favorite emerges in relation to alternatives.

That means identity is not just “what wins,” but “what it beats, what nearly beats it, and why.”

